msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:124
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "The YunoHost project simplified the classic installation as much as possible in order to avoid as many people as possible being lost with questions that are too technical or related to specific cases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:126
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the expert mode installation, you have more possibilities, especially concerning the exact partitioning of your storage media. You can also decide to use the classic mode and [add your disks afterwards](/admin/tutorials/external_storage).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:127
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "Summary of the steps in expert mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. Select `Expert graphical install`.\n"
"2. Select your language, location, keyboard layout and possibly your timezone.\n"
"3. Partition your disks. This is where you can set up a RAID or encrypt all or part of the server.\n"
"4. Specify a possible HTTP proxy to use for the installation of the packages\n"
"5. Specify on which volumes grub should be installed\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:135
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "Regarding partitioning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:138
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "In general, we recommend against partitioning `/var`, `/opt`, `/usr`, `/bin`, `/etc`, `/lib`, `/tmp` and `/root` on separate partitions. This will prevent you from having to worry about full partitions that could crash your machine, cause app installations to fail, or even corrupt your databases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:140
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "For performance reasons, it is recommended to mount your fastest storage (SSD) on the root `/`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:142
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you have one or more hard drives to store data, you can choose to mount it on one of these folders depending on your usage.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Path                             | Contents |\n"
"| -------------------------------- | -------- |\n"
"| `/home`                          | User folders accessible via SFTP |\n"
"| `/home/yunohost.backup/archives` | YunoHost backups to be placed ideally elsewhere than on the disks that manage the data |\n"
"| `/home/yunohost.app`             | Heavy data from YunoHost applications (nextcloud, matrix...) |\n"
"| `/home/yunohost.multimedia`      | Heavy data shared between several applications |\n"
"| `/var/mail`                      | User mail |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:152
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:119
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you want flexibility and don't want to (re)size partitions, you can also choose to mount on `/mnt/hdd` and follow this [tutorial to mount all these folders with `mount --bind`](/admin/tutorials/external_storage).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:153
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "About encryption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:156
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "Be aware that if you encrypt all or part of your disks, you will have to type the passphrase every time you restart your server, which can be a problem if you are not on site. There are however solutions (quite difficult to implement) that allow you to type the passphrase via SSH or via a web page (search for \"dropbear encrypted disk\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:157
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:124
#, no-wrap
msgid "About RAID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:160
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "Keep in mind that:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/regular_computer.mdx:164
#: docs/admin/05.get_started/20.install_on/virtualbox.mdx:131
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"- the disks in your RAIDs must be of different brands, wear and tear or batches (especially if they are SSDs)\n"
"- a RAID 1 (even without a spare) is more reliable than a RAID 5 from a probability point of view\n"
"- hardware raids are dependent on the raid card, if the card fails you will need a replacement to read and rebuild the array\n"
msgstr ""

